{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659870"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:16:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:16:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21081"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21081"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13956"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108816"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13956"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33676"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39808"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108816"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA histological section of epithelial tissue from the oesophagus is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the type of epithelium shown in the image?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Simple cuboidal epithelium","Pseudostratified columnar epithelium","Simple columnar epithelium","Stratified squamous epithelium","Simple squamous epithelium"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows \u003Cstrong\u003Estratified squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterised by multiple layers of cells with flattened cells at the surface. The basal layer contains cuboidal cells that progressively flatten as they move toward the surface. This type of epithelium is found in areas subject to mechanical stress such as the oesophagus, oral cavity, and vagina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E consists of a single layer of flat, scale-like cells. It is found in areas where filtration or diffusion occurs, such as alveoli and endothelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple cuboidal epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E consists of a single layer of cube-shaped cells. It is found in ducts and tubules of glands and in the kidney tubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple columnar epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E consists of a single layer of tall, column-shaped cells. It is found in the digestive tract and parts of the respiratory tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudostratified columnar epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E appears stratified but all cells contact the basement membrane. It typically has cilia and is found in the respiratory tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStratified squamous epithelium provides protection against mechanical abrasion and is well-suited for the oesophagus, which experiences friction during swallowing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Stratified squamous epithelium consists of multiple layers of cells with flattened cells at the surface.","Stratified squamous epithelium provides protection against mechanical abrasion and is found in areas subject to wear and tear.","The basal layer of stratified squamous epithelium contains cuboidal or columnar cells that undergo mitosis to replace cells shed from the surface."],"references":["Epithelial Tissues: Stratified Squamous Epithelium. Flikr. Image accessed under CC0 1.0 license: https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/. Accessed at: https://www.flickr.com/photos/146824358@N03/41994229312/in/photolist-2oKxGxc-7eL3Ko-2oWsaGA-2oWgHiU-2pyd1vX-gX8D5o-2oW8yM9-2kxSxxZ-CpKjsS-BBY282-PLSgd7-JmtCCF-dnuPkj-r7vKE-dQYcmk-Cx1jKY-C1NyGn-MWGnVG-24i4zKE-4r3f4K-UTdbtG-N4QhEh-bBj6R3-x1m84-BBNguj-TR9rQy-JGpWCo-TU2J6K-26yQYYD-NiwJTs-5wdGoy-5w9mU8-5wdGpo-N4ft1b-5KAa4k-5w9mT8-dC8t4y-5w9mTx-TU2HVz-qkZxk-JGpWv9-6tNzqS-JGpWtf-26YTpjq-JGpWxd-JGpWFQ-9SUjW-26LDeu4-MabaLJ-4gPsz/","Oescelik A, DeMeester SR. General anatomy of the esophagus Thorac Surg Clin 2021; 21:289-97."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91179"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21081"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21816"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21816"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DR90RvI4yHtdmarJUzOS1hz6Cq0IrJ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DR90RvI4yHtdmarJUzOS1hz6Cq0IrJ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":846}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91179"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T15:35:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T15:36:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13956"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108816"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type